==English==

===Etymology===
First coined in 1382, from {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|zele|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|zel|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term|zēlus|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|ζήλος||zeal, jealousy|tr=zēlos|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}, from {{term|ζηλόω||to emulate, to be jealous|tr=zēloō|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}. Cognate to {{term|jealous|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK|US}} {{IPA|/ziːl/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/zi:l/}}
* {{audio|en-us-zeal.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|iːl}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# The [[fervor]] or tireless [[devotion]] for a person, cause, or ideal and determination in its furtherance; [[diligent]] [[enthusiasm]]; [[powerful]] [[interest]].
#* Dryden
#*: '''Zeal''', the blind conductor of the will.
#* Bible, Romans x. 2
#*: I bear them record that they have a '''zeal''' of God, but not according to knowledge.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A [[zealot]].
#: {{rfquotek|Ben Jonson}}

